The kittens may favor the yellowish bag as it is smaller. I don't think the scent was the deciding factor there. Cats like spots that just fit right to their body size, as it makes them feel saver. If it is a cat-sized opening, the largest thing that could attack them is a cat-sized creature. It is also more comfortable, as they can snuggle against the walls. Of course materials and shape play a factor as well, as having a scratchable surface helps the cat making it part of their territory.

To the catnip i can only say that I don't think it is worth to buy it at all. Not every cat likes it and not all so called 'catnip' attracts cats. I have several species of cat mint in my garden and not a single cat cares about it. They may chew on one of their leaves, but the bamboo on the other side of the garden gets much much more such action. It seems to be more about the shape and structure of the leaves rather than its smell and maybe even taste. Anything that is grass-shaped and has no poison will do just fine. (Larger leaves are prefered, though) I used just wheat most of the time, as you can buy germinable wheat in almost every super market. Half a kilo will last you 1-2 years easily - and costs less than one pot of ready to eat cat grass.

My cats like to chew on strand maths/raffia maths (essentially bound together hay in structure and smell) as well. I think most cats would do. Dried catnip leaves/stems and blossoms don't get too much attention in comparison.
As for the socks: Just put anything into it. It doesn't need to be catnip. It only has to be interesting. I never met a cat that liked them stuffed with plain fabric/tuff, but crumbled up paper, leaves or - yet again - hay will make for interesting sounds and texture. It is of course much cheaper as well.

If you're like me and work from home or spend a lot of time on your computer. Have a "decoy" keyboard nearby to keep them off of yours. Cats engage in mimicking behavior which is why they always want to get involved with things you're doing, for example laying on your keyboard while you use it. It works for other things as well. So when you notice a cat getting in the way of you doing something, try and set up a decoy near you that has similar items to what the cat is tryingto involve themselves with. They'll feel happy since they're mimicking you, and they won't be directly in your way. Win win. I use a cheap keyboard from a secondhand store as my decoy.

This would be a somewhat time consuming project depending on how far you want to take it (IE integrating a battery compartment into the cat tree so you don't have wires showing and such) but the end result would keep kittens pretty well interested.
